  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in New York who’s been living in the city for over 20 years, I’ve always valued the trustworthiness of information—especially when it comes to health and wellness. Given that I don’t use social media, I’ve never been exposed to the kind of fake content that plagues others. But I know how quickly misinformation can spread, and it’s something I’ve seen firsthand through my clients. When I’m working with people who do use social media, I often emphasize the importance of critical thinking and verifying facts before sharing. For instance, a client once shared a post claiming that a certain exercise could cure diabetes, which turned out to be a hoax. I reminded them to check the source and consult a medical professional. My own approach to managing misinformation is rooted in the values I learned growing up as an immigrant family in New York. My parents, one of whom has a bachelor’s degree and the other only a primary school education, taught me the importance of questioning and verifying information, even when it’s presented as factual. I’ve also found that staying informed through reliable channels like health organizations and certified fitness professionals helps me stay grounded. While I don’t use social media myself, I understand that for many people, especially those who are anxious about the world around them, fake content can be overwhelming. That’s why I encourage my clients to focus on their own health and well-being, rather than getting caught up in online chaos. In a world where misinformation spreads so fast, it’s crucial to prioritize critical thinking and seek out trusted sources—whether it’s a doctor, a reputable health organization, or even a friend who’s been through it all.",
